  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The poet is resolved to pray without intermission, and he prays; fore his soul is comfortless and sorely tempted by the vast distance between the former days and the present times. According to the pointing, והאזין appears to be meant to be imperative after the form הקטיל, which occurs instead of הקטל and הקתילה, cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 94:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 43:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 17:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and the mode of writing הקטיל, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 142:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 8:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and frequently; therefore et audi  equals  ut audias (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 21:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). But such an isolated form of address is not to be tolerated; והאזין has been regarded as perf. consec. in the sense of ut audiat, although this modification of האזין into האזין in connection with the appearing of the Waw consec. cannot be supported in any other instance (Ew. ֗234, e), and Kimchi on this account tries to persuade himself to that which is impossible, viz., that והאזין in respect of sound stands for ויאזין. The preterites in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 77:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " express that which has commenced and which will go on. The poet labours in his present time of affliction to press forward to the Lord, who has withdrawn from him; his hand is diffused, i.e., stretched out (not: poured out, for the radical meaning of נגר, as the Syriac shows, is protrahere), in the night-time without wearying and leaving off; it is fixedly and stedfastly (אמוּנה, as it is expressed in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 17:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") stretched out towards heaven. His soul is comfortless, and all comfort up to the present rebounds as it were from it (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 37:35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 31:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). If he remembers God, who was once near to him, then he is compelled to groan (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 55:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 55:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and on the cohortative form of a Lamed He verb, cf. Ges. ֗75, 6), because He has hidden Himself from him; if he muses, in order to find Him again, then his spirit veils itself, i.e., it sinks into night and feebleness (התעטּף as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 107:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
